{"timestamp": "2026-05-26T06:34:37.029615+00:00", "user_id": "test-pipeline-001", "message_id": "b95b7ab8-8db3-4c1e-a081-87d9af858cac", "error_type": "constraint_violation", "raw_output": "A blood sugar reading of 200 mg/dL is higher than the usual target range, but it’s something you can manage with the right steps. First, don’t panic — stress can make blood sugar go even higher, so take a few slow breaths and sit down.\n\nCheck if you’ve eaten recently, missed your medication, or had something sugary like sweet chaaya, juice, or a dessert. If you haven’t taken your diabetes medicine today, take it now as prescribed. Do not take extra medication or insulin unless your doctor has specifically told you what to do in this situation — adjusting doses on your own can be dangerous.\n\nDrink a glass of plain water and take a gentle 15–20 minute walk, like walking around your home or compound. This can help bring your sugar down. Avoid sugary drinks, juices, or fruit right now. Recheck your blood sugar after 2 hours to see if it’s coming down.\n\nOne thing you can do today: if you often see high readings, write down your sugar levels, what you ate, and whether you took your medicine — this helps your doctor adjust your plan if needed. If your sugar stays above 200 for more than two days, or if you feel very thirsty, tired, or unwell, please contact your doctor.", "fallback_applied": true, "attempt_count": 1, "extra": {"violations": ["specific_dose_mg"]}}
